comments.body:
We need to replace old notes with new values in a first pass, then in a second pass add boilerplate to all collections.

Spreadsheet is here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/10YGW44UwmvOaaKJz4KqFqZ_Ym5dUGFcgmYeidciJ7Z0/edit#gid=0

Edit: we are replacing all existing phystech notes regardless of what the spreadsheet says.

For preservation reasons, original analog and digital media may not be read or played back in the reading room. Users may visually inspect physical media but may not remove it from its enclosure. All analog audiovisual media must be digitized to preservation-quality standards prior to use. Audiovisual digitization requests are processed by an approved third-party vendor. Please note, the transfer time required can be as little as several weeks to as long as several months and there may be financial costs associated with the process.
Requests should be directed through the [Ask Us Form.](https://library.princeton.edu/special-collections/ask-us)
If possible, we want the boilerplate to be the first note in the array.
Ruby prepend method: https://ruby-doc.org/3.1.4/Array.html#method-i-prepend

- [ ] run boilerplate on staging

pulfalight.title: Adds online access banner to collection page
Solr is timing out when running AspaceIndexJobs

comments.body:
Things we learned:

* The heap on lib-solr-prod4 was still high because it hadn't been restarted since the changes to its configuration. Restarting it brought down the heap.
* Faraday was timing out waiting for the solr update. We can increase the timeout in `blacklight.yml` to let it wait longer. 15 minutes let some index.
* The pulfalight-worker1 box was out of space because it dumped the EAD to the log every time it failed, and it failed every time.
* We learned that the solr boxes have no firewalls restricting their communication.
